{
  "doc_id": "20622",
  "text": "Mitochondria are a major source of ROS and are also easily damaged by ROS [CITATION_1] . This mitochondrial oxidative damage contributes to dysfunction and cell death in a range of diseases [CITATION_2] . Therefore, there has been an interest in developing mitochondria-targeted antioxidants designed to ameliorate mitochondrial oxidative damage [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The rationale for the development of mitochondria-targeted antioxidants is that although oxidative damage to mitochondria contributes to a wide range of pathologies, antioxidant therapies have performed poorly in clinical trials [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . As discussed in the extensive critical summary of clinical trials to date [CITATION_7] , trials of many of the most common antioxidants, such as vitamin E and vitamin C, showed no benefit to patients. Failures such as this could be because oxidative damage is not a major contributor to disease. Alternatively, the lack of success may be because of the small proportion of the antioxidant in vivo actually located in the mitochondria, where it is needed most to counteract mitochondrial oxidative damage. Mitochondria-targeted antioxidants were developed to overcome this targeting limitation [CITATION_8] .",
